From the nmap scan, I notice port 139 is open. I ran the command enum4linux 192.168.138.148 to perform some basic SMB enumeration and identified plenty of information. I notice the hostname is RED. There are two additional SMB shares: kathy and tmp where guest users have access. If there are any interesting files inside the shares, maybe I can access them? The tool also found a bunch of different users on the machine. I will begin enumerating the SMB shares first.


Using the command smbclient \\\\192.168.138.148\\tmp, I connected to the tmp SMB share on the target machine as shown in the image above. There is one file that called ls that is accessible to me. Using the command get ls, I downloaded this file on my attack machine.


The content of ls file is shown above. In Linux, the command ls is used for directory listing. Is this a potential payload as the output of the ls file is a directory listing? I will need to check on this a bit more later.


Using the command smbclient \\\\192.168.138.148\\kathy, I connected to the kathy SMB share. This user has interesting SMB share. There are two directories: kathy_stuff and backup. Inside the kathy_stuff directory, there are two files: vsftpd.conf and wordpress-4.tar.gz. I downloaded both files using mget * inside this directory, and entering y for both user prompts. Inside the kathy_stuff directory, there is one file called todo-list.txt. I downloaded this file on my machine again using the command mget * and y. Time to check the contents.


The file todo-list.txt contains the message shown in the picture above. It mentions the user kathy is responsible for performing backups for the company. If that is the case, she could potentially have backed up sensitive files with hardcoded credentials. Inside the kathy_stuff share, the two files vsftpd.conf and wordpress-4.tar.gz could have important data. It is also worth mentioning the description of the user kathy SMB contained the message Fred, What are we doing?; therefore, this new username fred is something new. Time to check the wordpress-4.tar.gz file now. I am interested in searching for config files.

So far, the user elly stands out to me the most as this user has appeared a lot during enumeration; for example, the FTP, the note left behind by john for elly, etc. I reset the box due to VPN issues. Now the target machine has the IP address of 192.168.181.148.

Exploitation

Exploitation: Bruteforcing the FTP & SSH


After getting stuck. I decided to check out the FTP once again. I attempted to bruteforce the password of the user elly using the wordlist rockyou.txt, but this was not helpful at all. Then using the command cat /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt | grep "elly" > elly.txt, I filtered the entries in rockyou.txt to contain the string elly. This is a common practice as users like to have their name in their password. When attempting to bruteforce, I had no luck. However, when I tried it is reverse cat /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt | grep "ylle" > elly.txt, I got a hit. The credentials elly:ylle works in FTP application.


Once I gained access to the FTP application as the user elly, I found a bunch of directories and files available on the FTP share. One of the interesting entryt I found is the passwd file. I downloaded this file on my machine using the command get passwd. This file contains the information:

In total there are twenty-six users on the machine that look promising. And once again, I decided to perform a bruteforce attack. Earlier I successfully bruteforced the password of user elly, as the password was in reverse order. But this time, I decided to use the flag -e nsr to try the null, same, and reverse passwords offered by hydra.


I ran the command hydra -L users.txt -e nsr ssh://192.168.181.148 and obtained the result shown in the image above. The user SHayslett is using the password as their username SHayslett.


To obtain a low privilege access on the target machine, I ran the command ssh SHayslett@192.168.181.148 to login to the target machine as the user SHayslett. The password of this user is SHayslett. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user SHayslett.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User SHayskett to User root via Sensitive Password Inside .bash_history of User JKanode

Running the command find /home -readable -ls -type f 2>/dev/null | grep ".bash_history" returns the result shown in the image above. Since there are plenty of users on the machine, I ran this command to identify the readable .bash_history files of the users. In total, there are six files that contain information due to the file size. These files could contain useful commands entered by the users.


I ran the command cat /home/JKanode/.bash_history and obtained the output shown in the picture above. The command sshpass -p JZQuyIN5 ssh peter@localhost is the most interesting. The password JZQuyIN5 was used to login as the user peter.


I ran the command su peter and the password JZQuyIN5, and obtained a shell as the user peter. Running the command sudo -l shows the entry (ALL : ALL) ALL. Since I have the password of this user, I ran the command sudo bash to obtain a root shell. As shown in the picture above, now I have a root access on the target machine :)
